description:
The LAMASUS Land Use Management (LUM) Geodatabase is a harmonised spatial dataset developed to represent land use management patterns across Europe in a consistent and comparable way. It integrates multiple input sources, including land cover products (e.g., CORINE Land Cover time series), statistical datasets, and ancillary geospatial information, to derive a coherent representation of how land is managed over time.

The dataset provides spatially explicit layers (primarily at ~1 km resolution and aggregated administrative levels such as NUTS regions) that describe dominant land use management categories such as cropland, grassland, forest, and urban areas. It is designed as an analytical and modelling product rather than a direct observation dataset, supporting the assessment of land use dynamics, environmental impacts, and policy-relevant indicators across European territories.
The dataset is archived on Zenodo (https://zenodo.org/records/13254324
), with additional information available on the official project page (https://www.lamasus.eu/resources/lum-geodatabase/
) and an interactive visualizer accessible at https://lumexpv1.accms.iiasa.ac.at/en/home/.”
